'''Komori Katte Shrine''' (こもりかってじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kuroda, Kisogawa-chō|Q17210627|qid=Q17210627|1=Kisogawa-chō Kuroda}}, {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q270810|qid=Q270810|1=Ichinomiya, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It is identified with “Kuroda Shrine” in Haguri District, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|qid=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.

=== Overview ===
*The founding period is unknown. Since {{ill|lt=Ichinobe Oshiwa no Miko|Q2297842|qid=Q2297842|1=Ichinobe no Oshiwa}}, father of Princes Oke and Woke, is said to have been killed by Emperor Yūryaku in {{ill|lt=Emperor Ankō|Q361010|qid=Q361010|1=Emperor Ankō}} 3 ({{ill|lt=456|Q30432|qid=Q30432|1=456}}), it is presumed this shrine had already been founded before then. Kuroda Shrine was the formal name, but it was also called Komori Katte Shrine at that time.
*It was long regarded as an important shrine. There are records of imperial offerings in the reigns of {{ill|lt=Empress Kōken|Q232955|qid=Q232955|lt=Empress Shōtoku|1=Empress Kōken}} and {{ill|lt=Emperor Uda|Q349267|qid=Q349267|1=Emperor Uda}}, and in {{ill|lt=951|Q23654|qid=Q23654|1=951}} ({{ill|lt=Tenryaku|Q1346281|qid=Q1346281|1=Tenryaku}} 5), an envoy of {{ill|lt=Emperor Murakami|Q374015|qid=Q374015|1=Emperor Murakami}} prayed there for recovery from illness.
*In {{ill|lt=1582|Q6719|qid=Q6719|1=1582}} ({{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 10), it was rebuilt by {{ill|lt=Sawai Katsushige|Q11553123|qid=Q11553123|1=Sawai Katsushige}}, lord of {{ill|lt=Kuroda Castle (Owari Province)|Q11678587|qid=Q11678587|lt=Kuroda Castle|1=Kuroda Castle}} and chief retainer of {{ill|lt=Oda Nobukatsu|Q3044815|qid=Q3044815|1=Oda Nobukatsu}}.
*In the Edo period it was called “Kuroda Daimyōjin” and “Hakusan Shrine.” When it became gōsha for the northwestern Haguri District area in {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}} (Meiji 5), it was renamed Komori Katte Shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|lt=Haraedo no Ōkami|Q11588504|qid=Q11588504|lt=Seoritsuhime-no-Mikoto|1=Haraedo no Kami}}
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yodobime-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}} (Kokūtsuhime-no-Mikoto)
*:Child of {{ill|lt=Okinaga Sukune no Ō|Q11492327|qid=Q11492327|1=Okinaga no Sukunu no miko}} and elder (or younger) sister of {{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|qid=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}}.

=== Cultural properties ===
=== Ichinomiya City designated tangible cultural properties ===
* Waniguchi gong (craft) - late Muromachi period
* Image of Komori Kuroda Daimyōjin honji (painting)
* Ninja sword (craft) - early Edo period
* Bamboo spear (craft) - early Edo period

=== Transportation ===
*15 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Kisogawa Station|Q871019|qid=Q871019|1=Kisogawa Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Tōkaidō Main Line|Q1190152|qid=Q1190152|1=Tōkaidō Main Line}}.
*20 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Kuroda Station (Aichi)|Q6446282|qid=Q6446282|lt=Kuroda Station|1=Kuroda Station (Aichi)}} on the {{ill|lt=Nagoya Main Line|Q1137838|qid=Q1137838|1=Meitetsu Nagoya Main Line}} of {{ill|lt=Nagoya Railroad|Q30850|qid=Q30850|1=Meitetsu}}.
*1 minute on foot from “Matsuyama-higashi” stop on the Kisogawa/Kitagata route of {{ill|lt=i-Bus|Q11223722|qid=Q11223722|1=I-Bus}}.
*5 minutes on foot from “{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya Municipal Kisogawa Citizen’s Hospital|Q11352566|qid=Q11352566|lt=Kisogawa Citizen’s Hospital|1=Kisogawa Hospital}}” stop on the same i-Bus route.

=== Mikago Festival ===
A ritual held on lunar August 15. Images of Princes Oke and Woke are placed in {{ill|lt=kago|Q936754|qid=Q936754|1=Kago}} palanquins, taro is offered, and prayers are made for warding off misfortune and abundant harvest. This derives from the following tradition.

*{{ill|lt=Ichinobe Oshiwa no Miko|Q2297842|qid=Q2297842|1=Ichinobe no Oshiwa}}, father of Oke and Woke, was a prince of {{ill|lt=Emperor Richū|Q329704|qid=Q329704|1=Emperor Richū}}. {{ill|lt=Emperor Ankō|Q361010|qid=Q361010|1=Emperor Ankō}} (his nephew) intended to pass the throne to him, but in Ankō 3 ({{ill|lt=456|Q30432|qid=Q30432|1=456}}), Ankō was assassinated by {{ill|lt=Mayowa no Ōkimi|Q11582590|qid=Q11582590|1=Prince Mayowa}}. Prince Ōhatsuse (later {{ill|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|Q357235|qid=Q357235|1=Emperor Yūryaku}}), who had long resented this, lured Ichinobe Oshiwa no Miko to hunting grounds at Kayano in {{ill|lt=Ōmi Province|Q843882|qid=Q843882|1=Ōmi Province}} and shot him.
*The brothers Oke (later {{ill|lt=Emperor Ninken|Q357266|qid=Q357266|1=Emperor Ninken}}) and Woke (later {{ill|lt=Emperor Kenzō|Q360966|qid=Q360966|1=Emperor Kenzō}}), fearing further danger, fled the capital. On their way toward {{ill|lt=Masumida Shrine|Q705916|qid=Q705916|1=Masumida Shrine}} in Owari, they passed through Mino and reached Kuroda Shrine.
*They stopped their palanquin in the forest of Kuroda Shrine and spent the night inside. It was the full-moon night of lunar August 15. Villagers treated them kindly with dishes of {{ill|lt=taro|Q227997|qid=Q227997|1=Taro}}. In thanks, the princes offered dew from taro leaves to Kuroda Shrine, prayed for villagers’ happiness, and departed before dawn.

